data.content:
This is **C# 14's span overload resolution change**. In .NET 10, `array.Contains(num)` now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent `Span<T>`-based methods, so you get a runtime failure.

**Fix — force the `Enumerable` overload using one of these approaches:**

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);

// Option 3: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);
```

All three prevent the compiler from choosing the `Span`-based overload and keep the expression tree representable.
